After the Liberal International Order
Cambridge—Many analysts believe the Liberal International Order ended with the rise of China and the election of U.S. President Donald Trump.
But if Joe Biden defeats Trump in the November election, should he strive to revive it?
Perhaps the result is not so, but he must find some alternative.
Critics are correct in pointing out that the U.S.-led order after 1945 was neither truly global nor always very liberal.
It excluded more than half of the world, including the Soviet bloc and China, and included many authoritarian states.
American hegemony is always exaggerated.
Nevertheless, the most powerful countries must take the lead in creating global public goods, or they will not be provided — and Americans will suffer as a result.
The current pandemic is a good example.
A realistic goal of the Biden administration should be to establish rules-based international institutions with different member states participating in handling different issues.
Would China and Russia be willing to participate?
In the 1990s and the 21st century, neither country was able to balance U.S. power, while the U.S. operated above sovereignty, persisting in the pursuit of liberal values.
The U.S. bombed Serbia and invaded Iraq without the approval of the United Nations Security Council.
It also supported a 2005 UN General Assembly resolution on the "Responsibility to Protect," aimed at protecting citizens from their own governments' brutal treatment — a principle the U.S. later used in 2011 to justify bombing Libya to protect civilians in Benghazi.
Critics describe this record as the arrogance of Americans in the post-Cold War era — for example, when the NATO-led intervention in Libya ultimately led to a regime change, Russia and China felt deceived — while defenders of the operation describe it as the natural evolution of international humanitarian law.
In any case, the growing power of China and Russia more strictly limits liberal interventionist actions.
So what remains?
Russia and China emphasize the principle of sovereignty enshrined in the UN Charter, which stipulates that states may only wage war in self-defense or with the approval of the Security Council.
Since 1945, the occupation of neighboring countries' territories by force has been very rare, and whenever it occurs, it incurs high costs due to sanctions (as seen in Russia's annexation of Crimea in 2014).
Moreover, the Security Council frequently authorizes the deployment of peacekeeping forces in troubled countries, while political cooperation has successfully curtailed the proliferation of weapons of mass destruction and ballistic missiles.
This rules-based order dimension remains crucial.
Specifically regarding economic relations, the world needs to revise the rules.
Long before the pandemic, China's hybrid state capitalism supported an unfair mercantilist model that distorted the functions of the World Trade Organization.
The result will lead to the decoupling of global supply chains, especially in situations where national security is threatened.
Although China complains about the U.S. blocking companies like Huawei from building 5G communication networks in the West, the U.S. stance is consistent with sovereignty claims.
After all, China has blocked the operations of Google, Facebook, and Twitter in the country for security reasons.
Negotiating new trade rules will help prevent the escalation of decoupling.
Meanwhile, despite the outbreak of the current crisis, cooperation in key financial sectors remains very strong.
On the contrary, interdependence in the ecological field creates insurmountable obstacles in the face of sovereignty, as threats transcend national borders.
No matter how much economic globalization is hindered, environmental globalization will continue, as it is subject to biological and physical laws, which contemporary geopolitical logic has no effect on.
The above issues threaten everyone, but no single country is capable of solving them independently.
In issues such as the 2019 COVID-19 pandemic and climate change, power also possesses so-called positive-sum dimensions.
In such circumstances, merely thinking about exercising power over others is not enough.
We must also think in terms of exercising power in conjunction with other countries.
The Paris Climate Agreement and the World Health Organization are helpful to us and to others.
Since Nixon and Mao met in 1972, despite ideological differences, this has not hindered cooperation between China and the United States.
The challenge Biden faces is whether the United States and China can cooperate in producing global public goods while competing in traditional great-power domains.
Cyberspace is a new and important issue — because it has a transnational character in part, but is also controlled by sovereign governments.
The internet has already been partially fragmented.
Rules on internet free speech and privacy can be established within democratic countries, but these rules will not be recognized by authoritarian states.
As suggested by the Global Commission on the Stability of Cyberspace, if authoritarian regimes also wish to achieve connectivity, certain rules prohibiting tampering with the fundamental structure of the internet would also be in their interest.
But when they use proxies to wage information warfare or interfere in elections (practices that violate sovereignty), norms must be reinforced through rules such as those negotiated during the Cold War to limit the escalation of maritime incidents between the United States and the Soviet Union (although hostility in the ideological domain remains).
The U.S. and like-minded countries must publicly state the norms they intend to uphold and establish the necessary deterrents.
Sticking to liberal values in cyberspace does not mean the U.S. unilaterally disarms.
On the contrary, the U.S. should distinguish between permissible soft power such as public persuasion and hard power like covert information warfare, and the U.S. is certainly bound to retaliate when the other side launches covert information warfare.
Russia and China can be allowed to publicly broadcast programs and radio, but secret actions such as manipulating social media to achieve unified outcomes are not permitted.
And the U.S. will continue to criticize the human rights records of these countries.
Public opinion polls show that the U.S. public wants to avoid military intervention but does not want to withdraw from alliances or multilateral cooperation.
And the public still values these principles.
If Biden is elected, the issue he faces is not whether to restore the Liberal International Order.
The question is whether the U.S. can cooperate with its core allies to promote democracy and human rights while also working with a broader range of countries to manage rules-based international institutions needed to address transnational threats such as climate change, pandemics, cyberattacks, terrorism, and economic instability.
